Subjects covered in the series include solicitations; routine editing and proofreading issues; book design; contract negotiations; sales and royalties; awards; reprints; and film rights and adaptations.  Individuals represented include John Hall Wheelock (
                     Scribner's
                  ), Dewitt Wallace and Paul Palmer (
                     Reader's Digest
                  ), Selden Rodman (
                     Common Sense
                  ), Kyrill Schabert (Pantheon Books), George Stevens (
                     Saturday Review of Literature
                  ), and William Jovanovich (Harcourt, Brace and World and Harcourt Brace Jovanovich). Their letters contain discussion of general publishing issues as well as comments on Lindbergh's work and critiques of their own work and that of other authors they represent.  Lindbergh's substantial correspondence from Helen and Kurt Wolff can be found under Pantheon Books through 1960, and thereafter under Harcourt, Brace and World, and Harcourt Brace Jovanovich.  It reveals the intimate, interdependent working relationship between author and editor.  In addition to business details and general editing matters, their letters offer encouragement, suggestions for revisions, discussion of general theories of literary production, and comments on Lindbergh's style of creation and development as an author (see Series I Correspondence From Friends and Acquaintances, for the Wolff's personal correspondence with Lindbergh).  Charles Lindbergh took an active interest in the publication of Anne's diaries.  His correspondence with Helen Wolff and Harcourt Brace Jovanovich  can be found in the Charles A. Lindbergh Papers and contains information on contract issues, the gathering and copying of  diaries and letters, delivery of manuscripts, and editing revisions.

